  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3127858053" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3127858053" />
    <a title="ElsaMakotoRenge" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/56376620-elsamakotorenge"><img alt="ElsaMakotoRenge" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1596424324p2/56376620.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3127858053?book_show_action=true">Mar 18, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="ElsaMakotoRenge" class="user" itemprop="url" name="ElsaMakotoRenge" href="/user/show/56376620-elsamakotorenge">ElsaMakotoRenge</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/56376620-elsamakotorenge?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/56376620-elsamakotorenge?shelf=non-series-novels">non-series-novels</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/56376620-elsamakotorenge?shelf=books-that-irritate-me">books-that-irritate-me</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/56376620-elsamakotorenge?shelf=mystery">mystery</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/56376620-elsamakotorenge?shelf=2020-reads">2020-reads</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer3127858053&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3127858053" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2525192720879165254">I’m so disappointed. I really wanted to love this book! But I just didn’t.<br/><br/>While I don’t mind gloomy dreary books and enjoy them, I like them to have light at the end of the tunnel so to speak. (Ashes in the Snow, and Stain are recent reads that come to mind) This one didn’t. Whatever could go wrong went wrong and I wasn’t satisfied with the ending AT ALL.<br/><br/>Also, this is marketed as a murder mystery, and said mystery has so little bearing on the plot and really isn’t a mystery. Now I love historica</span>
  <span id="freeText2525192720879165254" style="display:none">I’m so disappointed. I really wanted to love this book! But I just didn’t.<br /><br />While I don’t mind gloomy dreary books and enjoy them, I like them to have light at the end of the tunnel so to speak. (Ashes in the Snow, and Stain are recent reads that come to mind) This one didn’t. Whatever could go wrong went wrong and I wasn’t satisfied with the ending AT ALL.<br /><br />Also, this is marketed as a murder mystery, and said mystery has so little bearing on the plot and really isn’t a mystery. Now I love historical fiction, mystery or not, so A Northern Light not being a mystery is fine, but then it shouldn’t be marketed as such. <br /><br />Mattie herself was incredibly frustrating as a character. Honestly she read more like a 21st century girl than 1906 girl for some reason and it felt jarring. (Though regardless I wouldn’t have liked her in a YA contemporary either.) <br /><br />I also hated the “romance” with Royal...like uhhhh....two teenage characters pawing each other is not romance. This was probably intentional, but why was EVERY SINGLE male character in this book insufferable/jerk/sexist/abusive/nasty? Every single one? Seriously? I mean, I’m all for girl power and fun feminist stories are cool, but there’s no need for the blatant...male-hating in this book, haha. I thought it was ridiculous. Even if I try to rationalize it as, well sexism was rampant in the early 1900s, it still doesn’t mean every.single. guy back then was a terrible person. <br />It seemed like marriage/having children was portrayed as something that sucks the soul out of girls and is awful, too. I didn’t care for that either.<br /><br />Finally, I just did not like the ending. I wanted to at least have Mattie contact her little siblings, but she doesn’t. She just seemingly abandons her family, and while her dad is a creep, her little sisters deserve to know what she’s doing.<br /><br />I look forward to picking up other Jennifer Donnelly books in the future because I LOVED her Waterfire Saga series, but A Northern Light missed the mark for me.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2525192720879165254" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


